node.text: Now with English subtitles! Yoel, a recent immigrant from Cuba (only 4 months in this country) finally is able to express what has been frustrating him for 36 years and the recent developments in Cuba.  Unfortunately, we still cannot say he can express this freely because we risk our seeing our families, our families lives, and the possibility of entering/leaving cuba because of the regimes control even outside the island.  But Yoel finally after 36 years can no longer take other people talking in front of him.  This is what he says about the embargo, oppression and life in cuba today.

node.title: English! A message from a recent Cuban immigrant

node.text:
Hi non Cuban 2 week old Cuban experts! I got a couple questions for you: How is Samsung, a brand that should be embargoed in Cuba, have a store in Havana? In what dimension Is a 55 inch tv that was purchased in bulk by the Cuban government resold at $10,000?  Riddle me the embargo here, please. This gusana doesn’t understand. 

Yes it took me 10 min and 6 attempts to get text to speech to say cojone right. 😂

node.text: Now with English subtitles! Yoel, a recent immigrant from Cuba (only 4 months in this country) finally is able to express what has been frustrating him for 36 years and the recent developments in Cuba.  Unfortunately, we still cannot say he can express this freely because we risk our seeing our families, our families lives, and the possibility of entering/leaving cuba because of the regimes control even outside the island.  But Yoel finally after 36 years can no longer take other people talking in front of him.  This is what he says about the embargo, oppression and life in cuba today.

node.text:
EXPLAINED: The cuban economy is very complex and blaming the downfall on the embargo lacks serious perspective in the many other factors that cause economies to collapse. Here are just some examples of internal domestic policies the Cuban government has implemented that don’t help in the situation. In fact, the inefficiencies are so well known that it is very common for Cubans to mention (quietly) the two embargos. But the workers of America won’t know that..... because they don’t ever actually talk to Cubans. They only speak over us. 

Design again by @juliettehelen. 

#soscuba #cuba #cubanembargo #handsoffcuba #abajoelbloqueo #endtheembargo #abajoladictadura #vivacubalibre #diazcanelsingao

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by Marissa Daniela - Cuba on July 26, 2021 tagging @juliettehelen. May be an image of animal, outdoors and text that says '#SOSCUBA A TALE OF 2 EMBARGOES @mimaincuba @juliettehelen'.

Photo by Marissa Daniela - Cuba on July 26, 2021. May be an image of one or more people and text that says '#SOSCUBA RESTRICTION ADDICTION @mimaincuba @mimaina @juliettehelen Granma CANCION PATRIA PROHIBIDO VIDA' PROHIBIDO AL EXTRANJERO VIAJES PROTESTAR IBIDO'.

Photo by Marissa Daniela - Cuba on July 26, 2021. May be an image of text that says '#SOSCUBA Cuban Economy is Complex Like all economies, Cuba's is a complex web dictated by policies the Cuban government has created. The US embargo isn't the only thing Ûhing directly affecting the suffering of the Cuban people. The dictatorship heavily participates. Here are some examples @mimaincuba @juliettehelen'.

Photo by Marissa Daniela - Cuba on July 26, 2021. May be an image of text that says '#SOSCUBA Acopio A state-run agricultural distribution agency. Farmers are mandated to sell a certain quota to the state (Acopio) and are disincentivized to create surplus because of the limited amount of crops that can be sold directly to consumers. Acopio sets prices and pays farmers in Cuban pesos, not hard currency. Frequently, they fail to pick up crops on time and over 25% of production is left to rot. This program directly affects the number of available crops on the market contributes the scarcity of basic staple items grown naturally on the island. @mimaincuba @juliettehelen'.

Photo by Marissa Daniela - Cuba on July 26, 2021. May be an image of tree, outdoors and text that says '#SOSCUBA Monetary Policy Introduction to dual currencies Most Cubans are paid in a worthless currency: Cuban pesos. However, most food items in markets with any surplus are sold in hard currency. The dual monetary policy has created an economic disparity between Cubans who have access to money outside the island, and those who do not. @mimaincuba ejuliettehelen'.

Photo by Marissa Daniela - Cuba on July 26, 2021. May be an image of one or more people and text that says '#SOSCUBA Lack of Economic Liberties Cubans cannot just open any business. They are limited to certain licenses the government provides. Most allowed businesses are "low-skilled meaning services like restaurants, barbershops, spas etc. Businesses that scale or integrate essential parts of the economy are not allowed and are directly controlled by the state, one giant corporation. @mimaincuba @juliettehelen'.

Photo by Marissa Daniela - Cuba on July 26, 2021. May be an image of one or more people and text that says '#SOSCUBA Economy protects the state, not the entrepreneur. The state, led by the communist party, has historically been volatile in its economic policies. At one moment it loosens restrictions and just like that it retakes and controls once business sector is becoming successful. As part of the communist ideology, becoming successful is not encouraged. Entrepreneurs are discouraged from Entrepreneurs innovating and creating when their businesses are not protected. @mimaincuba @juliettehelen'.
Photo by Marissa Daniela - Cuba on July 26, 2021. May be an image of text that says '#SOSCUBA All of these policies makeup what many Cubans on the island recognize as... @mimaincuba @juliettehelen'.
Photo by Marissa Daniela - Cuba on July 26, 2021. May be an image of text that says '#SOSCUBA The Internal Embargo. Cuba's suffering is more complicated than you think. @mimaincuba @juliettehelen'.

Photo shared by Marissa Daniela - Cuba on July 26, 2021 tagging @14ymedio, and @proyectoinventario. May be an image of one or more people and text that says '#SOSCUBA Listen to Cuban Voices @pedromonreal Twitter Cuban Economist @mdemirandap Twitter Cuban Economist) @14ymedio Independent Journalism in Cuba @invntario Independent Cuba Data Publishers @mimaincuba @juliettehelen'.

node.text:
NO THIS ISNT JUST COVID! For years Cubans have been protesting the injustices. I filmed this in 2018 and was so scared to upload it. In the most clandestina way, I passed it to @yusnaby who has been a silent partner in crime pushing our content out when I was too scared to do it.  In this video, an entire neighborhood in havana put water tanks out on the street to protect the lack of water for 11 days. Two blocks away is the @kempinskihavana, a 5 star luxury hotel in havana that won’t ever lack water for tourists.  The neighbors were so fed up. While Cubans just stood on the sidelines using the only weapon they have, a cellphone, I actively documented their grievances. 

Anyone who pushes this bullshit narrative of tje pandemic being what people are protesting against is blinded by their personal biases.  The i justices and ineficiencias of the cuban government have been normal day hush hush amongst almost every Cuban on the island.

node.text:
Abuela, born in Pinar del Río 1921 is 99 years old. She lived under Fidel Castro regime and saw the regime take away arms. She explains that she was sad when she saw the protests because she knew they wouldn’t win.  They don’t have arms.  The regime does and they beated, shooted and imprisoned many. When I asked her what she wanted for cuba she shouted Freedom! Not food or medicine. Freedom so they can find their own food with the work they do.  At 99 she’s still waiting, dreaming and praying, her island will one day be Free. 

#cuba #cubalibre #patriayvida #abajoladictadura

node.text:
This 26 de Julio isn’t just for “revolutionaries” it’s for the entire diaspora, the exiles, the recién llegados, the 2nd generation, the 3rd generation, the ones who love cuba, and the ones ON THE ISLAND to finally make an inclusive Cuba for EVERYONE. #PATRIAYVIDA 

#soscuba #abajoladictadura #cuba #26dejulio

May be an image of text that says '26 DE JULIO July 26th is marked as the beginning of the revolution led by Fidel Castro who attacked the Batista Regime in 1953. It later became a political organization that overtook the regime in 1959. It is celebrated each year Cuba @MIMAINCUBA'.

Photo by Marissa Daniela - Cuba on July 24, 2021. May be an image of text that says '67 YEARS LATER... protestors and activist in Cuba, exercising the same right Fidel used, are now imprisoned, jailed, and silenced if they have different opinions. @MIMAINCUBA'.

node.text: Voices in Cuba: a farmer explains to Yoel and I how the government mistreats farmers. The government, because of lack of gas and as he explained, desire, hasn’t collected his tobacco that was ready since may (recorded in August). So the tobacco leaves have been wasted.  Farmers are required to sell at least 90% of tobacco to the state. When the state doesn’t pick up crops, they don’t pay either leaving many farmers, like this man, feeling helpless.  These are the stories, voices and experiences in Cuba you will never get from statistics. These are the lives you’ll never hear from. And this is the news they will never air.  #vivacibalibre #soscuba #abajoladictadura

node.text: It’s getting exhausting

Zoila, born in 1920 (101 years old) in La Habana, Cuba came to the United States only 18 years ago. Like many Cubans who have United all over the world, she wants to see her country finally FREE. Que dios la bendiga. 

🎥: @_steph_espin_  Gracias por este video! 

#soscuba #vivacubalibre #abajoladictadura #diazcanelsingao #patriayvida

node.text:
Feeling so proud of my Yoe for expressing his mind, his opinion, and letting go 36 years of oppression, fear, and tears. It’s the first time in his life he was able to experience a basic humanity stripped of him for so long. 

Que orgullo me siento por mi yoe. ❤️❤️ 

Video: yoel trying to tell people not to tell press intervention because we are impeding protesters in cuba. No one wants intervention and the regime is using it for manipulation in cuba. We need to be smart. 

2. All our friends in pinar del rio coming out in moami.
